site: Ireland, Co Tipperary, Rock of Cashel, in a plain beneath the.
toSearch: Rock Of Cashel, Cashel, Co. Comté De Tipperary, Ireland
description: Made by joining together 4 thin plates, those in the part being smaller then those at the back, giving the appearance of a stud. The smaller plate ornamented with wheel-like figure of dots; attached by a recurved edge to an unornamented plate, which has an opening in the centre, this is joined to the edges of an opening in the 3rd plate, which is joined by an overlapping rim to the outermost plate. The latter is externally ornamented with 5 raised circles surrounded by dots placed on a five-limbed figure contained in a dotted circle. in the space between the central plates was found a small solid gold ball weighing .715 gms., Wilde:- "when found the plates were crushed flat & there were indentations of 3 such balls in both the external plates."
publications: Catalogue, p. 90-91. See also Proc. Royal Irish Academy VIII, p. 407.
remarks: Wilde stated that "this was probably a personal ornament, possibly an earring."

description: Dimensions: L 310mm; Wbl 58.9; Ws 29.6; Bs 28.3; DS 280; Wt. 431.9 g,Typology: fillets defining midrib marginally bowed in sympathy with blade outline: lozenge midrib with hints of emphasised ridge which becomes real rib on circular section socket, termination level with fillets; sub-rect. fillet bases; sl. angle in bl. edge close to its base gives suggestion of an obtuse 'barb' or offset; small penetration of blade by socket.,Manufacture: socket neat on reverse side but with irregular small step/groove on obverse - marking cg. fl. line; peg holes probably cast; good concave e. bev.; small perf. close to s.m. not obviously modern.,Condition: edge mainly good; tip blunted - sim. colour to rest; dent assoc. with diag.scratching on socket rev. - pres. modern.

associations: Probably one of the 5 bronze celts found 4-5 ft from the surface by a labourer, Wm. Pickering, when digging a drain about 20 yards SE of the crossing of the Crow Brook below Preston W.M.

remarks: This palstave fits closely on the (tracing of the ) drawing of an axe from the hoard which was (in 1880) in possession of Int. Hoper of Kinnersley W.M. It may well have been obtained by Miss. C. Eyton later than the publication of her book.
